    <h3>Call OSGi Bundle.</h3>
    <hr />
    <p>You can call your back-end OSGi bundle using your executable.</p>
    <p>Syntax : <code>var SampleClass = Java.type("org.wso2.carbon.uuf.sample.SampleClass");</code></p>
    <p>In your pom.xml;</p>
    Same as in osgi bundles; you need to explicitly
    <p>In your JS file;</p>
    <pre>
        function onRequest(env) {
            var PetsManagerServiceImpl = Java.type("org.wso2.carbon.uuf.sample.pets_store.bundle.impl.PetsManagerServiceImpl");
            var service = new PetsManagerServiceImpl();
            return {"helloWorldText" : service.getHelloMessage("John")};
        }
    </pre>
    <p>Then, you can use this variable in your handlebars;</p>
    <pre>
        \{{helloWorldText}}
    </pre>
    <h3>Notes:</h3>
    The above code will print "{{helloWorldText}}".
